  "prompt": "Cricket: Batsman strikes the ball, is caught by the bowler. But since the non-striker is a better batsman, and is out of his crease, the bowler removes the bails at the non- striker end and appeals for run-out. He does not appeal for caught and bowled. Which batsmen is legally out and why?",
  "response": "In this scenario, the **non-striker** is **legally out** due to a **run-out**. Here's why:\n\n1. **Batsman Strikes the Ball and is Caught by the Bowler**:  \n   When the batsman hits the ball and it is caught by the bowler, a **caught and bowled** dismissal could occur. However, **the bowler does not appeal for this dismissal**, so the striker is **not out** on this count.\n\n2. **Non-Striker is Out of the Crease**:  \n   The **non-striker** (the better batsman) is **out of his crease** at the time the bowler removes the bails. This is a case of **run-out**, specifically referred to as **Mankading** (though this term is not officially recognized in the laws of cricket).\n\n3. **Bowler Appeals for Run-Out**:  \n   The bowler **removes the bails at the non-striker's end** and appeals for a **run-out**. Since the non-striker was out of his crease, and the appeal is made, the **non-striker is out** under **Law 38 (Run Out)**.\n\n### Key Points:\n- The **non-striker** is legally out because he was out of his crease, and the bowler successfully appealed for a run-out.\n- The **striker** is not out because the bowler did not appeal for a **caught and bowled** dismissal.\n\n### Conclusion:\nThe **non-striker** is the batsman who is **legally out** under the **run-out** rule.",
